Duck Typing is a concept in programming that describes a design pattern where objects are considered to be compatible with other objects if they have the same interface. It's called "ducking" because it's analogous to the way ducks are compatible with water because they have a duck-like shape. In programming, this means that you can use objects of a type that have a different implementation of the interface, as long as they have the same method signature.

For example, in Duck Typing, you can use an object with a different implementation of the interface, but if it has the same methods as the object you're trying to use, it is compatible with it.

Here's a simple example to illustrate Duck Typing:

